help.default: In the chart format, ‘Overview’ displays a bar graph of the count (or rate) of cases on the first day of the month or year (point in time data). The chart format also displays a line graph of the number of opened cases and the number of closed cases for the entire month or year (cohort data). Each ‘Overview’ count or rate is available individually in the chart format. The table format always returns all the ‘Overview’ data.
help.sp_ooh_pit_counts: In the chart format, ‘Overview’ displays a bar graph of the count (or rate) of cases on the first day of the month or year (point in time data). The chart format also displays a line graph of the number of entries or cases opened and exits or case closures for the entire month or year (cohort data). Each ‘Overview’ count or rate is available individually in the chart format. The table format always returns all the ‘Overview’ data.
help.sp_ooh_pit_rates: In the chart format, ‘Overview’ displays a bar graph of the count (or rate) of cases on the first day of the month or year (point in time data). The chart format also displays a line graph of the number of entries or cases opened and exits or case closures for the entire month or year (cohort data). Each ‘Overview’ count or rate is available individually in the chart format. The table format always returns all the ‘Overview’ data.

display.help: Age references the child’s/youth’s age at the time of placement in out-of-home care.
Age references the child’s/youth’s age on the given date.

Age references the child’s/youth’s age at the time she/he was removed from their home and placed into out-of-home care (e.g., kinship care, foster care). Because the age categories are based on U.S. Census classifications, we are able to calculate the rate of cases (per 1,000) by age for the state or county.

Age references the child’s/youth’s age on a given date (i.e., the first day of the year or quarter). Because the age categories are based on U.S. Census classifications, we are able to calculate the rate of cases (per 1,000) by age for the state or county.

Age of children in the household is the filter used for Investigations & Assessments Trends and for all the In-Home Services measures. It references the ages of the children/youth in the household at the time the investigation/assessment was opened and at the time the family was receiving in-home service. The age categories follow U.S. Census conventions, therefore we are able to calculate the rate of cases (per 1,000) by age category for the Division of Children and Family Services Offices or Office Groups. Please see Filters Explained for more information on how to interpret the four age categories.
This is the county the data suggests the child/youth lived in prior to removal. You can select any of Washington State’s 39 counties; ‘All’ (the default) returns statewide data.
This is the county the child/youth was placed in on this date. You can select any of Washington State’s 39 counties; ‘All’ (the default) returns statewide data.

You can select re-entry to out-of-home care from reunification, adoption, or guardianship. Re-entry is calculated 48 months from the ‘Exit Cohort Year’ you have chosen. The default includes all three outcomes.
You can select exit from out-of-home care to reunification, adoption, guardianship, emancipation or other. The default selection is exits to all five outcomes.
This filter returns data on the number of siblings in a family in order to more clearly understand the configuration of siblings who are placed together.
You can filter for kinship placements only or for all types of placement (foster care, kinship care, group home, etc.).

Race and ethnicity categories are based on U.S. Census classifications. Races are above the line, ethnicities are below the line. Because the Census provides data on the races and ethnicities within geographic divisions, we are able to calculate the rate of cases (per 1,000) by race or ethnicity for the state, county, or Division of Children and Family Services Office. Note that each household or child has a race AND an ethnicity.
There are 43 DCFS Offices (Division of Children and Family Services) offices in Washington State.
There are 43 DCFS Offices (Division of Children and Family Services) offices in Washington State. In order to calculate Census-adjusted population based rates, some DCFS offices were grouped.

Cohort data for out-of-home care cases are aggregated into three COUNT TYPES. Counts/rates of ‘First Out-of-Home Care Case’ are generally the lowest count/rate, while ‘Unduplicated Out-of-Home Care Cases’ counts/rates of will be the highest. ‘Unduplicated Out-of-Home Care Cases’ are unique cases (i.e., the first out-of-home care cases per time period). See Interpreting Type of Count.

Point in time data for children in out-of-home care are aggregated into two COUNT TYPES. Counts/rates of ‘First Out-of-Home Care Case’ will be lower than the counts/rates of ‘All Out-of-Home Care Cases’ (which can include multiple episodes). ‘See Interpreting Type of Count.

Data for children in out-of-home care are aggregated into two COUNT TYPES. Counts/rates of ‘First Out-of-Home Care Case’ will be lower than the counts/rates of ‘All Out-of-Home Care Cases’ (which can include multiple episodes). ‘See Interpreting Type of Count.

Data are aggregated into three COUNT TYPES. Counts/rates of ‘First Investigation(s)’ are generally the lowest count/rate, while counts/rates of ‘All Investigations’ (households with repeat investigations) will be the highest. ‘Unduplicated Investigations’ counts unique cases (i.e., the first investigation per time interval). See Interpreting Type of Count.

Data are aggregated into three COUNT TYPES. Counts/rates of ‘First In-Home Service Case(s)’ are generally the lowest count/rate, while counts/rates of ‘All In-Home Service Cases’ (households with repeat in-home services) will be the highest. ‘Unduplicated In-Home Service Cases’ are unique cases (i.e., the first in-home service per time period). See Interpreting Type of Count.

There are five primary entry points, i.e., first point of contact with Children’s Administration. Currently, the Data Portal can return data for Child Protective Services (CPS) and ‘All’ entry points. CPS provides 24 hour, seven days a week intake, screening, and investigative services for reports/ referrals of alleged child abuse and neglect.

An allegation of child abuse, neglect, or any maltreatment can come from any person (mandated reporter or not). Social workers have the option of entering up to four types of maltreatment per case, meaning there will be more allegations than cases. Neglect and physical abuse comprise the bulk of allegations; due to the severity of sexual abuse, it is also included in the allegation filter. To determine how many cases have no allegations, subtract ‘Any Legal Finding’ from ‘All (With or Without Allegation).’

The courts become involved when there is a dependency proceeding or action. A dependent child is one who was abandoned, abused or neglected, or whose parents are incapable of adequately parenting. In this filter, ‘Immediate Dependency’ means a petition was filed within 45 days of the start of the out-of-home episode and ‘Eventual Dependency’ means the petition was filed more than 45 days after the start of the episode.

An allegation finding means that, more likely than not, the Children’s Administration Child Protection Services (CPS) investigator determined that child abuse or neglect did occur. To determine how many cases have no legal finding, subtract ‘Any Legal Finding’ from ‘All (With or Without Legal Finding).’

Some in-home services are paid by Children’s Administration (CA) or and some are not covered. Examples of paid services include case management and certain behavioral rehabilitation services. CA-paid services can be directly linked to a child or a family. Services that are not paid for by CA: cannot be linked to a child or family; are purchased in bulk; or are provided by a service provider or any entity other than CA (e.g., health care, employment services).

An out-of-home care episode begins with a state custody date and ends with a federal discharge date. Multiple placements into out-of-home placement settings can occur within a single episode. This filter allows you to determine how many episodes are greater than 7 days, 60 days, 1 year, or 2 years.

An out-of-home care episode begins with a formal custody date and ends with a formal discharge date to a permanency outcome. A child/youth in out-of-home care can have MULTIPLE PLACEMENTS WITN AN EPISODE. If, for example, you selected a four year period to examine, and within that time the child/youth had two episodes, with two placements in each episode, he/she would have had four placements.

In Washington State, anyone who has reasonable cause to believe that a child has suffered abuse or neglect can, in good faith, make a report. Mandated reporters (above the line) are required by law to report concerns to the local Children’s Administration office or to law enforcement.

The service categories above the line are generally in-home services. The services below the line tend to be services for families with children in out-of-home care. More about the following services can be found in the Glossary: Family Focused Services, Therapeutic Services, Receiving Care, Family Home Placements, Behavioral Rehabilitation Services, Other Therapeutic Living Situations, Specialty Adolescent Services, Respite Care, Sexually Aggressive Youth, Adoption Support.

The six Department of Social and Health Services (DSHS) budget categories include all the major IN-HOME budget categories. DSHS codes are provided for people familiar with Children's Administration budget categories.

This filter follows the cohort of households which received their (first) investigation/assessment within the cohort year(s) selected. Data on the percent of children re-referred are returned for up to 48 months following the selected cohort year.

The entry cohort you are following is that group of children/youth who entered out-of-home care in the chosen year. ENTRY COHORT YEAR choices begin January 2000 and end on the most recent year for which we have data. Because nearly all children/youth in out-of-home care have achieved permanency or turned 18 years old within four years, the default year is set approximately four years earlier than the most recent date and results are returned for up to 48 months.

The exit cohort you are following is that group of children/youth who exited out-of-home care in the chosen year. EXIT COHORT YEARS choices begin January 2000 and end on the most recent year for which we have data. Because the number of re-entries begins to level off after four years, the default year is set approximately four years earlier than the most recent year and results are returned for up to 48 months.

This filter follows the cohort of households which received in-home services in the selected cohort year(s). Data on the percent of children placed in out-of-homecare are returned for up to 48 months following the selected cohort year.
